Inorder traversal is not a unique identifier of BST. At the same time, both preorder and postorder traversals are unique identifiers of BST. But in Tree serialization problems -
Using Preorder + inorder; Postorder+inorder OR level order OR any other combination -
does not guarantee a unique traversal
There is an example where Preorder+postorder might not also work uniquely when there are duplicate nodes.
https://leetcode.com/problems/subtree-of-another-tree/editorial/

Hence, in case of Tree Serialization problems - we use:
Preorder Traversal (or postorder traversal) with markers for null node unique determines Binary Tree
But, even more efficient is KMP (Knuth-Morris-Pratt)


Ways to write a traversal code:
1. Iterative (Time Efficient, we use stacks to store full context)
2. Recursive (Intuitive and Easy)
3. Morris (Space Efficient, we just use right node values to store location of next parent node (not our own parent) we have to go )

4. Just traversing as needed (without stacks or queues)

So when does iterative actually win?
1. Deep trees / avoiding stack overflow
This is the only real efficiency argument. For a skewed tree with 10^5 nodes, recursion will stack overflow. An explicit stack on the heap won't.
2. Iterative post-order is a good example
Post-order recursively is clean. Iteratively, you have to fake the return-from-recursion state, which is exactly the state management overhead you're describing.
3. Morris Traversal — this is where you get genuine O(1) space by threading the tree itself, no stack at all. Thats a real efficiency win over both.



